IDENTIFY the lobe of the thyroid gland

Two parathyroid glands, superior and inferior, normally lie on the posterior surface of each lobe of the thyroid gland. However, these are structures that migrate to their position during embryological development and so occasionally one or more of these glands may be found in other locations. The parathyroid glands are essential in the regulation of calcium levels in the body and each has a diameter of about 5 mm. It is not necessary to identify the glands.
